up|52|NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On this hand, Liza should have started with 2@C rather than 1@S to establish the game force. Over 1@H, if you have a game forcing hand with a 5 card minor and 4 spades, you should start with the 5 card minor. This is true both in 2/1 and SAYC. When you later bid your spades, you have established a game force. Thus, for example, the auction 1@H-P-2@C-P-2@H-P-2@S establishes a game force.|
PG| ***** 88 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Having said that, let's talk about what opener does with 5 hearts and 4 spades. In SAYC, if it goes 1@H-P-2@C-P-?, opener cannot bid 2@S with a minimum opener because that is a reverse. 2@C is not a game force, so opener is not sure whether or not their side has game. Therefore a 2S reverse establishes a game force and should only be done with 15+.|
PG| ***** 89 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, in 2/1 there are 2 schools of thought about the auction 1@H-P-2@C-P-2@S. One school of thought is that the 2@S bid shows extra values (it is essentially a reverse) and is looking for slam. (Remember, in 2/1 the 2@C bid establishes a game force.) The other school of thought is that 2@S is simply bidding out opener's shape, and simply shows 5 hearts and 4 spades and does not show anything extra. |
PG| ***** 90 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I used to play the first way (where 2@S shows extra values). But Bergen recommends the 2nd way (where 2@S is simply showing opener's shape but nothing extra) so I switched to that. However, I think either approach is fine. But your partnership must agree. (I think Karen Walker discussed this in her article which was in our earlier mentoring session movie.)|
PG| ***** 91 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Another interesting point is what you do over 1@H with 4 spades and a 4 card minor playing 2/1. Most people would bid 1@S. However, Bergen recommends you bid 2 of the minor to establish the game force and show your spades later if need be. |
PG| ***** 92 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, if playing the Bergen style, the auction 1@H-P-2@C-P-2@S-P-3@S means it is very possible that responder only has 4 clubs and 4 spades. But if you play the style most people play, then that auction means responder has 5 clubs and 4 spades, because with 4 clubs and 4 spades responder would bid 1@S over 1@H. |
PG| ***** 93 ***** |


