ht|b|at|"In practice, opener's new suit response show a singleton (not a void) over 90% of the time, so I am going to presume that is what it shows in the discussion below."|
PG| ***** 129 ***** |


AT|
^*BMM: ^*NMel further explains the logic behind bidding 2N.|
PG| ***** 130 ***** |


AT|

"The reason we do it [bid 2N] is to determine the degree of fit of the two hands - for slam purposes. When responder bids Jacoby, only a rookie would be proud to arrive at game and make it. The issue is slam. Should we or shouldn't we?"|
PG| ***** 131 ***** |


AT|

"When responder hears that opener has a side singleton, she has to
(1) analyze how well the two hands mesh and 
(2) make a bid that - given the new information about opener's singleton - either shows optimism or pessimism about slam."|
PG| ***** 132 ***** |


AT|
^*BMM: ^*NNext he has a trip in the memory lane and explains his love for rock-and-roll and particularly for "All Or Nothing At All" by Frank Sinatra, Ol' Blue Eyes, which was Frank's first hit for Columbia records, Billboard #1 in 1943--|CP|1|AT|^*Hen.wikipedia.org/wiki/All_or_Nothing_at_All^*N|CP||AT|.|
