AT| 

Those who want to hear that song hey can click this |CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.youtube.com/watch?v=u7klm1GS3v8^*N|CP||AT| link. The lyric is at the end of this presentation. After his long trip to 40s and 50s he continues.|
PG| ***** 134 ***** |


AT|

"Anyway, back to Jacoby 2NT and how my Frank Sinatra Rule works. Let's say opener shows a singleton. Now, if responder has either the Ace or no honor cards in that suit, she should be optimistic about slam because she has no wasted values. That's where the ^*BAll^*N (just the Ace) or ^*BNothing at All^*N (no honor cards - none) come in. With either of holdings, responder must make a bid that expresses optimism about slam. That can be done by:|
PG| ***** 135 ***** |


AT|

1. Bidding three of the agreed trump suit.
2. Bidding a new suit, which in this situation is a "control" bid. "Partner, I have first-round control of this suit - the Ace."
3. Bidding Blackwood.
4. Bidding slam right then and there (not at all recommended)."|
PG| ***** 136 ***** |


AT|

"Any other honor cards (Kings, Queens or Jacks) in the suit partner is short in are wasted values opposite the singleton (I'll show you examples right away). Those wasted honors make responder's hand weaker than it looks, so she should mentally turn over these wasted honor cards and discount them from her point count. Now she should count her points, and see if she still wants to broach slam. If not, she should make a bid that expresses pessimism about her side's chances for slam. There is only one such bid: four of the agreed trump suit. But enough talk, here are some examples."|
PG| ***** 137 ***** |


